{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17522466","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17522466"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T14:45:37+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T14:45:37+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13831"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13831","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13831"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.17,0.71,0.09,0.01,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6448"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"53611"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6448","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6448"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13831"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"39070"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"4"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"281"},{"type":"tags","id":"1155"},{"type":"tags","id":"3696"},{"type":"tags","id":"8189"},{"type":"tags","id":"9735"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"12749"},{"type":"contributions","id":"12750"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"53611","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/53611"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 72-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a three-month history of palpitations, increased frequency of bowel motions, and puffiness around her eyes and face. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. On examination, she has a pulse rate of 98/min, blood pressure 120/70 mmHg, respiratory rate 14/min, and temperature 36.2\u00b0C. Exophthalmos is present. The lower limbs appear abnormal (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following antibody tests would be MOST informative in determining the underlying cause of this patient\u0027s presentation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Anti-thyroid peroxidase antibodies","TSH receptor antibodies","Anti-thyroglobulin antibodies","Anti-triiodothyronine antibodies","Anti-thyroxine antibodies"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient\u0027s symptoms along with the examination findings of exophthalmos and pretibial myxoedema are highly suggestive of Graves\u0027 disease. Pretibial myxoedema is due to the accumulation of excess glycosaminoglycans in the dermis and subcutaneous layer of the skin, and gives a characteristic lumpy and swollen appearance. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETSH receptor antibodies\u003C/strong\u003E are the most specific test for diagnosing Graves\u0027 disease. These antibodies stimulate the TSH receptor, leading to increased thyroid hormone production and the characteristic features of Graves\u0027 disease. In this case, the presence of TSH receptor antibodies would confirm the diagnosis of Graves\u0027 disease as the underlying cause of the patient\u0027s myxoedema.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAnti-thyroid peroxidase antibodies\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003Eanti-thyroglobulin antibodies\u003C/strong\u003E are commonly found in autoimmune thyroid diseases, including Hashimoto\u0027s thyroiditis and Graves\u0027 disease. However, they are less specific for Graves\u0027 disease compared to TSH receptor antibodies (90-99%), compared to anti-thyroid peroxidase antibodies (50-80%) and anti-thyroglobulin antibodies (50-70%). While these antibodies might be elevated in this patient, they would not be as informative as TSH receptor antibodies in determining the specific cause of the presentation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAnti-triiodothyronine antibodies \u003C/strong\u003Eand \u003Cstrong\u003Eanti-thyroxine antibodies\u003C/strong\u003E are not real tests. The terms \u0027triiodothyronine\u0027 and \u0027thyroxine\u0027 refer to T3 and T4 respectively. \u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Myxoedema can be a presenting feature of Graves\u0027 disease.","TSH receptor antibodies are the most specific test for diagnosing Graves\u0027 disease."],"references":["Campbell K, Doogue M. Evaluating and managing patients with thyrotoxicosis. Australian Journal for General Practitioners. 2012;41:564-72. Available at: https://www.racgp.org.au/afp/2012/august/evaluating-and-managing-patients-with-thyrotoxicos","Pretibial myxoedema. In: DermNet NZ [Online]. Available from: https://dermnetnz.org/topics/pretibial-myxoedema"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"39070"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13831"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"20778"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"20778","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/20778"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/d6dlPc8do36dg3tYtSMP6q03YbNvZI.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/d6dlPc8do36dg3tYtSMP6q03YbNvZI.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":768,"height":1024}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"39070","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/39070"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-09-23T12:40:37+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-09-23T12:41:18+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6448"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"53611"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"4","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf6c","name":"Endocrinology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt